---
description: Guidelines for git commit messages using Conventional Commits for BetAgent.
alwaysApply: false
---

## Format

1. Single header line: `<type>(<optional-scope>): <imperative subject>`
2. Optional blank line, then body (bullets or prose) explaining what and why.
3. Optional footer lines: `BREAKING CHANGE: ...`, issue refs (`Fixes #42`), or tracker IDs if the team still links tickets in footers only.

## Types (common)

Use lowercase type from the Conventional Commits spec: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `perf`, `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore`, `revert`. Prefer the narrowest accurate type.

## Scope

- Prefer a monorepo scope: `web`, `api`, `ingest`, `worker`, `prisma-client`, `graphql`, `domain`, `ui`, `repo` (root tooling), or Nest module name when it clarifies the blast radius.
- Omit scope when the change is broad or cross-cutting.

## Title rules

- Imperative mood (`add`, not `added` or `adds`).
- ~50 characters target; hard cap ~72 for the full header line including type, scope, and colon.
- No trailing period on the subject line.

## Breaking changes

Either append `!` after type or scope (`feat(api)!: ...`) or add a `BREAKING CHANGE:` paragraph in the body describing migration impact.

## Example

```text
feat(worker): harden BullMQ enqueue idempotency

- Add deterministic job identifiers for match analysis backlog replays.
- Document retry caps for the match analysis queue producer.
- Extend worker metrics to separate duplicate suppressions from failures.
```
